	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 10-20-2004 <font color="#FEDE01">09:45 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">In light of the Writing Contest two.  I am whipping up another Story of Gnarm's Adventures in Norrath.  Since I participated last year (and placed second and got tons of board pp that I have no idea what to do with) If I do happen to place in the contest, I will defer my prize to another worthy Writer.<br />
<br />
Unfortunately this looks like another long one and it's gonna be broke into parts just like the last one.  You may want to read my <a href="http://www.eqcleric.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&threadid=5372" target="_blank">first story</a> to get some background on what is going on here.   With that, here is part one:<br />
<br />
PART 1: The Journey Ends<br />
<br />
The thumping of children’s feet echoed through the walls of Kaladim.  The children hurried to Deep in the eastern tunnels, to the storyteller’s house.<br />
<br />
Gnarm Silverhand sat on his porch overlooking the street; he could hear the children coming.  They would want stories; they would want to hear grand tales of great adventurers, of epic battles, of dwarfs defending their homeland, stories of his youth.  The old dwarf leaned back in his chair, and took a deep puff from his pipe.  To a keen eye the hint of a smile could be seen behind the dwarf’s heavy beard as he watched the children settle into place in front of him.  <br />
<br />
“Now let me see …where were we?”  Gnarm couldn’t help but laugh as all the children yelled out a different place they remembered the last story had ended.  “Now now, dern children…No discipline!  If’n I had da mind an body to I’d take ye all o’er me knee right now!  But since ye can’t come to any sort of agreement I gonna have to just start where I wants too.”<br />
<br />
“It t’were nearly a hunnerd seasons ago as we walked the fields of the great snow wasteland…”<br />
<br />
_______________________________________________<br />
<br />
The snow swirled and whipped across the great open plains as the companions moved forward.  Their year long trek was coming to a close…the last of the Dwarfsmasher clan was hiding out not far north of them.  Their clan hunted to near extinction, this clan had been particularly hard to find, adept at covering their tracks, Gnarm and Graydon had spent months tracking these four down, months of twists and turns.  The others didn’t know, the rest of the clan had never been in this position, this last group knew, and they hid, they knew they were now the hunted.  They were doing everything they could to not be found.  But in the end, as with all the others of this Frost Giant clan, the companions had found their trail.<br />
<br />
Graydon dismounted his horse at the top of the ridge.  “There, the cave, that’s where they are.”<br />
<br />
Gnarm plodded up the ridge and peered down at the cave, no signs of activity could be seen, though the blowing snow would cover that up quickly.  “Aye, lets set up camp an have a bit ta eat, its been a long trip no sense ending it on an empty stomach.” <br />
<br />
Gnarm built a fire and began to roast some mutton they had picked up at the last town.  When it was done he offered some to Graydon knowing the fallen paladin would not accept it.  Gnarm sighed as his good friend rejected the meat.  <br />
<br />
The dwarf looked at his friend and could see the grief in his face; the pain had taken its toll on Graydon.  His friend had lost so much more than his son, his wife had died shortly after the events in Thurgadin, still pregnant with their second child, his god and his church had exiled him for his quest of vengeance.  This was all there was anymore for the ex-paladin his way of payback against the gods for their destruction of his life and of course to the giants for taking his son.  Gnarm had tried, by Brell he had tried, to dissuade the human from this quest of his.  Gnarm loved to kill giants as much as the next guy, but was the cost to high?  Gnarm often wondered if his friend of so many seasons had truly been lost to the blood rage a year ago in Thurgadin.  But for all of his pleading Graydon’s mind would not be changed, and Gnarm could not abandon his friend.<br />
<br />
Dinner was done and packed up; the two friends tied their horses to a nearby tree and moved toward the cave.<br />
<br />
The two reached the mouth of the cave and stopped and stared inside for a moment, making no attempt to conceal themselves.  Gnarm quickly uttered a prayer to Brell, and the two were washed over in a soft light blue glow.  Gnarm could feel his thoughts sharpen, quickening his ability call on the abilities granted to him by Brell.  Graydon drew his magnificent twin long swords, Gnarm could hear that distinct hum that the swords made when they were unsheathed.  He could see his friend fall into “blood rage” a place the paladin seemed to fall into more and more since that fateful day.  A place that turned a noble paladin into a feared killing machine.  Gnarm felt a twang of remorse as he thought that, this rage was destroying his friend…how long could Graydon remain able to pull out of this rage when the battle is over, how long until Graydon started killing everything in his path, friend or foe?<br />
<br />
As Gnarm pondered this, Graydon charged into the cave.  Snapped from his thoughts the dwarf raced after “Dern Impatient Humans!”<br />
<br />
The four giants were quite surprised to see the seven foot, white haired human barge into their temporary home.  The “guard” at the door didn’t even see his death coming, his back to the entrance he only saw the tip of Balance, as Graydon’s off hand sword was known, protruding from his chest was the last sight the giant saw as he fell to the cold earth.  The other giants scrambled for their weapons to defend against this deadly foe.  They didn’t notice the dwarf rush in behind until one of them was struck by the priests holy blast as he reached for his axe.<br />
<br />
“Yar!  Two down two to go!  Which one ye got Gray?”  Gnarm, caught up in the love of killing giants, yelled to his companion.  But Graydon didn’t respond, he never did, not anymore.  Of course, Gnarm knew that Graydon would go after the bigger of the two giants, so the battle priest leapt at the smaller of the two bringing his hammer in an overhead arc bringing it down heavily on the surprised giants shoulder.  Sending the giant reeling backwards, eventually crashing to the floor.<br />
<br />
Gnarm shook of the effects of his disorienting leap, raised his hammer and stared at the sprawled out giant.  “Come on get up, gimme a bit o’ a challenge frosty!”  Gnarm tapped his hammer on the palm of his hand, waiting patiently for the giant to stand.<br />
<br />
The giant saw the dwarf, and seeing an opening raised his sword and swung at the dwarf…or where the dwarf had been.  Gnarm easily sidestepped the attack and counterattacked with a blow to the back of the giants neck as he rushed by, the crack of bone could be heard through out the cave and the giant collapsed in a heap.<br />
<br />
Gnarm then turned to his friend who stood over a very bloody giant swords sheathed, hair soaked in blood, staring at the giant he had just slain.  “It’s done.  The Dwarfsmasher Frost Giant clan is no more.”<br />
<br />
Graydon’s swords flashed into his hands and he turned toward the dwarf.<br />
<br />
“Gray?  You alright?”  Gnarm called to his friend.  But Gnarm could see that there was no getting to his friend, he was still in the blood rage, still running on his subconscious.  Gnarm took a step back, if Graydon meant to attack him then he was a dead dwarf, there wasn’t a man on Norrath who could match Graydon in battle.  As he back peddled to the wall, ‘Wait this isn’t a wall’ Gnarm thought as he spun to face what was behind him.<br />
<br />
“Inkiiiiiiiiiii” Was all the dwarf could get out as a lightning bold struck his chest and sent him hurdling toward the actual walls of the cave.  The cleric slammed hard into the wall but did not fall to the floor.  The Dark elf one hand pointed at him, was holding him in place with her evil lightning spell.  The lighting flowed through his body, Gnarm could feel his body cooking from the inside.  ‘Brell save us’ Gnarm muttered mostly in his mind.<br />
<br />
He watched as Graydon was hit by the same bolt but did not go flying, the Knight continued plodding forward, he couldn’t feel pain in this place after all.  Gnarm saw the dark elf  appear behind Graydon and tried to warn his friend but only could manage a gargled wimper.  He watched helplessly as the elf plunged his sword into the back of the paladin, to the hilt.  He wanted to scream he wanted to use his god given powers to aid his friend, but he could do nothing but watch.<br />
<br />
Symbios and Balance, the twin swords, flashed and the dark elf’s head rolled across the cave floor, coming to rest beneath the lightning suspended dwarf, his body momentarily still clenching the sword in the knight’s back.<br />
<br />
Graydon fell to a knee, some pain can not be ignored…the thief’s sword pulled him from the rage.  He tried to call upon his god to heal his wounds but there was no answer.  He could feel the lighting, he could see Gnarm twitching from the power frying his body.  Graydon pooled all his energy, pushing the pain away he raised his sword and threw it at the dark elf mage with all of his strength.  The sword struck the wizard in the shoulder sending him sprawling on his back, while ending the his lightning spells.<br />
<br />
Gnarm’s body crashed lifelessly to the floor.  Graydon tried to stand and finish off the wizard but he could not, his strength left him and he fell to his hands and knees, he felt the heat of the wizard’s next spell…then the darkness overcame him…<br />
<br />
To be continued soon...</font></p>
	
